The paper discusses the comparison of citation counts and indexing speed in Google Scholar and Scopus, which are relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. The focus on open access journals and institutional repositories suggests relevance to digital libraries (cs.DL). The analysis of citation impact and sources is relevant to information retrieval (cs.IR) and cybersecurity (cs.CY). The discussion of double citation counts and concept-based citation indexes suggests relevance to cryptography (cs.CR) and databases (cs.DB).
